This paper is about statistical parsing and machine learning for Classical Arabic, which falls under the category of computational linguistics (cs.CL). The paper also discusses the development of a formal representation for annotation and a resource for machine learning, which could be relevant to the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper uses volunteer crowdsourcing for annotation, which could be relevant to the sub-category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also discusses the use of graph transformations and joint dependency-constituency parsing, which could be relevant to the sub-categories of information retrieval (cs.IR) and cybernetics (cs.CY).
